Jumping over words with CTRL-LEFT/CTRL-RIGHT should be more intelligent. For example if the caret \(\*\) is located in

use \*Test::Foo;

Then pressing CTRL-RIGHT should move it before :: and not before the semicolon.

Also, punctuation should cause word stops in literals, e.g.

print "This is \*some.thing\n";

The caret should jump right before the dot in this case.

If a selected block of text is indented with spaces pressing Shift+Tab should delete the number leading of spaces that matches the displayed tab width. Currently this works only if "Use spaces instead of tabs" option is set.

Example: create a new file and enter 2 lines:
use strict;
use warnings;
prefixed by 4 spaces. Select those lines and press Shift+Tab. Leading spaces should be deleted \(assuming "Displayed tab width" option is set to 4\).

